    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix integer underflow in M2AP ID management functions\n\n### Summary\nThe M2AP ID management code was vulnerable to integer underflow issues due to lack of bounds checking on UE ID parameters. When invalid UE IDs were passed to functions like `m2ap_set_ids`, they could cause out-of-bounds array access, leading to memory corruption and unpredictable behavior including integer underflow that produced unexpectedly large unsigned values downstream.\n\nThis fix adds proper bounds checking to all M2AP ID management functions that use UE IDs as array indices.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/M2AP/m2ap_ids.c`: Added bounds checking to prevent out-of-bounds array access in all functions that take UE ID parameters\n- Functions protected include: `m2ap_set_ids`, `m2ap_release_id`, `m2ap_id_set_target`, `m2ap_id_set_state`, `m2ap_set_reloc_prep_timer`, `m2ap_set_reloc_overall_timer`, and all getter functions\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the original issue:\n1. Call `m2ap_set_ids` with a negative UE ID or UE ID >= M2AP_MAX_IDS\n2. Observe memory corruption as the function writes to invalid memory locations\n3. This can manifest as integer underflow when corrupted data is later interpreted as unsigned values\n4. Symptoms include segfaults, incorrect timer calculations, or unexpected behavior in M2AP handover procedures\n\nThe fix ensures all such functions validate their UE ID parameters before accessing the `ids` array, preventing the memory corruption that leads to downstream integer underflow issues.\n"
}